{{Infobox person | name = Dorothy Lee Bolden | birth_date = October 13, 1923 | birth_place = [[Atlanta, Georgia]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2005|7|14|1923|10|13}} | death_place = Atlanta, Georgia | occupation = Domestic Worker | organization = National Domestic Worker's Union of America | movement = [[Civil Rights Movement]] }}
'''Dorothy Lee Bolden''' (October 13, 1923 – July 14, 2005) was the founder of the National Domestic Worker's Union of America and worked to fight for [[women's rights]] and bring [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregation]] to an end.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/atlanta/obituary.aspx?pid=14586794|title=Dorothy Bolden Obituary|last=Powell|first=Kay|date=July 18, 2005|website=|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=November 3, 2016}}</ref> Bolden began working as a [[domestic worker]] at the age of nine. She would eventually utilize her past experiences to form the Domestic Worker's Union in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Through the Domestic Worker's Union, thousands of women have secured better pay and working conditions throughout the United States.
== Early life == Dorothy Lee Bolden was born on October 13, 1923 in [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Notable Black American Women|last=Smith|first=Jessie|publisher=Gale Research|year=1996|isbn=0-8103-9177-5|location=Detroit, Michigan|pages=Pages 37–38|chapter=Dorothy Lee Bolden|quote=|via=}}</ref> Bolden was born to Georgia Mae Patterson Bolden and Raymond Bolden.<ref name=":0" /> Both of her parents provided for their family, her mother was a housekeeper and her father was a chauffeur.<ref name=":1" /> Early education was difficult for Bolden due to poor eyesight. After a fall that damaged her [[optic nerve]] at the age of three, she didn’t gain her vision until the age of nine.<ref name=":0" /> She started working at the age of nine as a domestic worker and would continue in this work for forty-nine years.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|title=The Colombia Documentary History of American Women Since 1941|last=Sigerman|first=Harriet|publisher=Colombia University Press|year=|isbn=0-231-11698-5|location=New York|pages=Pages 295–303|chapter=You Can't Talk About Women's Rights Until We Include All Women|quote=|via=}}</ref> Bolden went to E. P. Johnson Elementary School and then [[David T. Howard High]] School.<ref name=":0" /> However, she only attended ninth grade and then had to stop because she needed to financially support herself. As a young woman, she traveled to Chicago to go to a school for dress designers, but her poor eyesight hindered her education. During World War II, Bolden also worked at [[Sears]] and the National Linen Service, where she recognized the early efforts for unionization and labor rights.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Household Workers Unite|last=Nadasen|first=Premilla|publisher=Beacon Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=Boston|pages=227}}</ref> [[Martin Luther King Jr.|Martin Luther King Jr]]. was an early influence in Bolden’s life, who was her neighbor at the time of the [[Civil Rights Movement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/1282515896/DAA52660C80E46F7PQ/3?accountid=14868|title=Black Women and Organizations|last=Malveaux|first=Julianne|date=16 Feb 2012|website=|publisher=Washington Informer|access-date=17 Nov 2016}}</ref>
== Career == Bolden became an activist well before the re-emergence of the civil rights movement in the 1960s. In the late 1940s, Bolden refused a request from her boss, a white woman, to stay late and wash the dishes. Her boss alerted local police, who responded by taking her to a county jail for a psychiatric evaluation. In an oral history interview from 1995, Bolden recalled the severity of the incident. "They told me I was crazy because I had talked back to a white woman, and called in some psychiatrists to prove it," said Bolden. "A white woman’s word was gospel, and two psychiatrists actually thought I was crazy… This was the way you got locked up…This was the system."<ref name=":7" />
With the help of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., Bolden was able to build relationships with families all over Atlanta.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=http://aarlarchives.blogspot.com/2011/11/mrs-dorothy-lee-bolden-founder-and.html|title=Mrs. Dorothy Lee Bolden, Founder and President of The National Domestic Worker's of America, Inc.|last=Zafir|first=Ayannah|date=November 19, 2011|website=Archives Library Associate|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Women were able to open up to Bolden about their experiences as domestic workers. Life for domestic workers was very challenging. During the 1960s, domestic workers endured 13 hour workdays and received as little as $3.50.<ref name=":3" /> However, in 1968, Bolden started discussions with other unions about beginning to organize a national union for domestic workers. The union helped improve the wages and working conditions of domestic workers in Atlanta and served as an example for other domestic workers all across the country.<ref name=":5">{{Cite book|title=Black Women In America, Second Addition|last=|first=|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2002|isbn=0195156773|location=Oxford|pages=|chapter=Bolden, Dorothy Lee|quote=|via=}}</ref> Bolden eventually gathered 13,000 women from ten different cities, benefiting from job referrals and organizations. The union helped to increase wages and working conditions for domestic workers. Also members were taught how to work out problems with their employers.<ref name=":5" /> Bolden became an icon in Atlanta due to all the help that she gave to domestic workers. The records of this union are kept at the organization's office and in the Southern Labor Archives at [[Georgia State University]].<ref name=":6">{{Cite book|title=The Harvard Guide to African-American History, Volume 1|last=Higginbotham|first=Evelyn|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=2001|isbn=0-674-00276-8|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> Under her leadership, the National Domestic Worker's Union fundamentally influenced the treatment of domestic workers. Bolden was central to actions that increased Atlanta wages by 33% over two years and won workers' compensation and [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] rights for all domestic workers.<ref name=":7">{{cite web|last1=Drummond|first1=Traci|title=Dorothy Bolden gave voice to Atlanta’s "Help"|url=https://blog.library.gsu.edu/2011/09/07/dorothy-bolden-gives-voice-to-atlanta%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%9Chelp%E2%80%9D/|website=Georgia State University Library Blog|publisher=Georgia State University|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref>
Bolden was also responsible for registering thousands of African Americans to vote. Her work improved the living conditions of many residents throughout Atlanta.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=http://digitalcommons.auctr.edu/dissertations/3032/|title=They led and a community followed: the community activism of Ella Mae Brayboy and Dorothy Bolden in Atlanta, Georgia|last=Harrison|first=Christy|date=2007|website=|publisher=ETD Collection for AUC Robert W. Woodruff Library.|access-date=November 17, 2016}}</ref> Bolden's efforts gained the attention of the [[Nixon Administration]] and she was appointed to an advisory committee on social services and welfare.<ref name=":3" />
== Personal life == Bolden married her first husband in 1941 but that ended in divorce.<ref name=":0" /> Later on, she married Abram Thompson and they had six children together- Frank, Avon Butts, Dorthy Ingram, Altenmiece Knight, Abram and Anthony.<ref name=":0" /> To support her family, Bolden had to work in many different jobs including the [[Greyhound Bus Station (Montgomery, Alabama)|Greyhound bus station]], Linen Supply Company, [[Sears|Sears Roebuck]], and [[Railway Express Agency|Railroad Express]].<ref name=":0" /> Although Bolden was a domestic worker, she did not accept jobs that did not involve child care.<ref name=":4" /> She loved working with children and seeing them develop into young adults.<ref name=":4" /> Bolden died in Atlanta on July 14, 2005.<ref name=":1"/>
